AN ACT relating to [peace officers;] public safety; creating the Purple Ribbon
Task Force on Firefighter and Peace Officer Wellness; setting forth the
membership and duties of the Task Force; and providing other matters
properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 This bill creates the Purple Ribbon Task Force on Firefighter and Peace Officer Wellness
2 to review the existing policies of this State concerning personal wellness initiatives that
3 account for the mental and physical health of firefighters, peace officers and other law
4 enforcement personnel. This bill also: (1) prescribes the membership and duties of the Task
5 Force; and (2) requires the Task Force to submit a written report describing its work and
6 recommendations for transmittal to the Senate and Assembly Standing Committees on
7 Government Affairs for the 84th Session of the Legislature.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. 1. The Purple Ribbon Task Force on Firefighter and Peace
2 Officer Wellness is hereby created. The Task Force consists of the following nine
3 members:
4 (a) Two members appointed by the Majority Leader of the Senate;
5 (b) One member appointed by the Minority Leader of the Senate;
6 (c) Three members appointed by the Governor;
7 (d) Two members appointed by the Speaker of the Assembly; and
8 (e) One member appointed by the Minority Leader of the Assembly.
9 2. To the extent practicable, membership of the Task Force must include,
10 without limitation:

Senate Amendment No. 604 to Assembly Bill No. 433 First Reprint Page 4
1 (a) A representative from a local government;
2 (b) A representative of an employee organization, as defined in NRS 288.040,
3 that represents peace officers or a labor organization, as defined in NRS 288.048,
4 that represents peace officers;
5 (c) A resource officer with a behavioral health background;
6 (d) A representative from a state law enforcement agency, including, without
7 limitation, the Department of Public Safety or the Department of Corrections; and
8 (e) A representative of an employee organization, as defined in NRS
9 288.040, that represents firefighters [from a local government employer, as
10 defined in NRS 288.060.] or a labor organization, as defined in NRS 288.048,
11 that represents firefighters.
12 3. The Task Force shall:
13 (a) Review the existing policies of this State concerning personal wellness
14 initiatives that account for the mental and physical health of firefighters, peace
15 officers and other law enforcement personnel; and
16 (b) Recommend personal wellness initiatives for state and local law
17 enforcement agencies and fire departments.
18 4. The members of the Task Force serve without compensation.
19 5. Each member of the Task Force who is an officer or employee of the State
20 or a local government must be relieved from his or her duties without loss of
21 regular compensation so that the member may prepare for and attend meetings of
22 the Task Force and perform any work necessary to carry out the duties of the Task
23 Force in the most timely manner practicable. A state agency or local government
24 shall not require an officer or employee who is a member of the Task Force to make
25 up the time the member is absent from work to carry out his or her duties as a
26 member, and shall not require the member to take annual vacation or compensatory
27 time for the absence.
28 6. The Task Force shall, at its first meeting, elect a Chair and Vice Chair from
29 among its members.
30 7. The Task Force shall meet upon the call of the Chair or a majority of the
31 members of the Task Force.
32 8. A majority of the members of the Task Force constitutes a quorum for the
33 transaction of business, and a majority of those members present at the meeting is
34 sufficient for any official action taken by the Task Force.
35 9. The Task Force may apply for and accept any gift, donation, bequest, grant
36 or other source of money to carry out the duties of the Task Force.
37 10. The Task Force shall prepare and submit a written report to the Director
38 of the Legislative Counsel Bureau for transmittal to the Senate and Assembly
39 Standing Committees on Government Affairs for the 84th Session of the
40 Legislature. The report must include, without limitation, a summary of the work
41 and recommendations of the Task Force.
42 Sec. 2. The members of the Purple Ribbon Task Force on Firefighter and
43 Peace Officer Wellness must be appointed pursuant to section 1 of this act not later
44 than October 1, 2025.
45 Sec. 3. This act becomes effective on July 1, 2025, and expires by limitation
46 on June 30, 2027.

